Many items in a capitalist society are assigned monetary worth, and access to products and services is often based on one's capacity to pay for them. However, it is not correct to state that everything has a cost. Some things are deemed priceless, such as human life, freedom, and justice, among others. Furthermore, many individuals and organizations, such as non-profit, volunteer, and philanthropic organizations, seek to give products and services that do not have a monetary value, such as education, health care, and assistance to the less fortunate. There are also other activities that are regarded invaluable and are not commercialized, such as art and culture. So, although the notion of everything having a price is prevalent in certain elements of our society, saying that everything has a price is not totally correct. 